title.narrative: MATERNAL, NEONATAL AND CHILD HEALTH

description.narrative: National policies, evidence, and institutional and professional capacities and budgets are in place to provide quality, evidence- based, equity focused, fiscally sustainable, perinatal and immunization services to all mothers, newborns and young children., which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care (Covid), Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition In Early Childhood (Covid), Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Girls and boys from conception to age 6, especially the most marginalized and those living in humanitarian settings, and their parents/families will benefit from high-impact health, nutrition and other interventions that support nurturing care for early childhood development, enabling children to survive and thrive.

title.narrative: National policies, evidence, and institutional and professional capacities and budgets are in place to provide quality, evidence-based, equity focused, fiscally sustainable, perinatal and immunization services to all mothers, newborns and young children.

description.narrative: Despite the burden of COVID-19, the health system was further improved for breastfeeding promotion and protection. The capacities of neonatal intensive care units (NICUs) to provide life-saving family-oriented services to premature and sick children has been strengthened. The health system was alerted to improve the quality of perinatal mortality data and to initiate causality analysis of neonatal mortality on the national level. Mobilizing national partners for improving rapidly decreased coverage of routine immunization resulted in their limited but increased engagement in supporting the worst-off districts. Over 600,000 doses of COVID-19 vaccines were procured and delivered through COVAX. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:04/01/2022
